[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:hocon-config/hocon] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:hocon-config/hocon] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:hocon-config/hocon] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:hocon-config/hocon] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:hocon-config/hocon] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:hocon-config/hocon] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Custom data types are allowed, but YAML natively encodes scalars (such as strings, integers, and floats), lists, and associative arrays (also known as maps, dictionaries or hashmaps).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] These data types are based on the Perl programming language, though all commonly used high-level programming languages share very similar concepts.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The colon-centered syntax, used for expressing key-value pairs, is inspired by electronic mail headers as defined in RFC 822, and the document separator `---` is borrowed from MIME (RFC 2046).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Escape sequences are reused from C, and whitespace wrapping for multi-line strings is inspired by HTML.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Lists and hashes can contain nested lists and hashes, forming a tree structure; arbitrary graphs can be represented using YAML aliases (similar to XML in SOAP).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML is intended to be read and written in streams, a feature inspired by SAX.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Support for reading and writing YAML is available for many programming languages.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Some source-code editors such as Vim, Emacs, and various integrated development environments have features that make editing YAML easier, such as folding up nested structures or automatically highlighting syntax errors.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The official recommended filename extension for YAML files has been `.yaml` since 2006.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] In 2024, the MIME type `application/yaml` has been finalized.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML (/ˈjæməl/, rhymes with *camel*) was first proposed by Clark Evans in 2001, who designed it together with Ingy döt Net and Oren Ben-Kiki.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Originally YAML was said to mean *Yet Another Markup Language*, because it was released in an era that saw a proliferation of markup languages for presentation and connectivity (HTML, XML, SGML, etc.).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] A cheat sheet and full specification are available at the official site.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The following is a synopsis of the basic elements.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML accepts the entire Unicode character set, except for some control characters, and may be encoded in any one of UTF-8, UTF-16 or UTF-32.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Conventional block format uses a hyphen+space to begin a new item in list.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Optional inline format is delimited by comma+space and enclosed in brackets (similar to JSON).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Keys are separated from values by a colon+space.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Indented blocks, common in YAML data files, use indentation and new lines to separate the key/value pairs.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Inline blocks, common in YAML data streams, use comma+space to separate the key/value pairs between braces.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] There are two ways to write multi-line strings, one preserving newlines (using the `|` character) and one that folds the newlines (using the `>` character), both followed by a newline character.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] By default, the leading indentation (of the first line) and trailing whitespace are stripped, though other behavior can be explicitly specified.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Folded text converts newlines to spaces and removes leading whitespace.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Objects and lists are important components in yaml and can be mixed.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The first example is a list of key-value objects, all people from the Smith family.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The second lists them by gender; it is a key-value object containing two lists.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Features that distinguish YAML from the capabilities of other data-serialization languages are structures, and data and composite keys.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML structures enable storage of multiple documents within a single file, usage of references for repeated nodes, and usage of arbitrary nodes as keys.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] For clarity, compactness, and avoiding data entry errors, YAML provides node anchors (using `&`) and references (using `*`).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] References to the anchor work for all data types (see the ship-to reference in the example below).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Below is an example of a queue in an instrument sequencer in which two steps are referenced without being fully described.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Explicit data typing is seldom seen in the majority of YAML documents since YAML autodetects simple types.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Data types can be divided into three categories: core, defined, and user-defined.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Core are ones expected to exist in any parser (e.g. floats, ints, strings, lists, maps, ...).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Many more advanced data types, such as binary data, are defined in the YAML specification but not supported in all implementations.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Finally YAML defines a way to extend the data type definitions locally to accommodate user-defined classes, structures or primitives (e.g. quad-precision floats).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML autodetects the datatype of the entity, but sometimes one wants to cast the datatype explicitly.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The most common situation is where a single-word string that looks like a number, Boolean or tag requires disambiguation by surrounding it with quotes or using an explicit datatype tag.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Not every implementation of YAML has every specification-defined data type.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] These built-in types use a double-exclamation sigil prefix (`!!`).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Particularly interesting ones not shown here are sets, ordered maps, timestamps, and hexadecimal.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Here is an example of base64-encoded binary data.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Many implementations of YAML can support user-defined data types for object serialization.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Local data types are not universal data types but are defined in the application using the YAML parser library.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Local data types use a single exclamation mark (`!`).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML supports composite keys, which consist of multiple values.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Such keys are useful for coordinate transformations, multi-field identifiers, test cases with compound conditions, and the like.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Data-structure hierarchy is maintained by outline indentation.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Notice that strings do not require enclosure in quotation marks.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The specific number of spaces in the indentation is unimportant as long as parallel elements have the same left justification and the hierarchically nested elements are indented further.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] This sample document defines an associative array with 7 top level keys: one of the keys, "items", contains a 2-element list, each element of which is itself an associative array with differing keys.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Relational data and redundancy removal are displayed: the "ship-to" associative array content is copied from the "bill-to" associative array's content as indicated by the anchor (`&`) and reference (`*`) labels.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Optional blank lines can be added for readability.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Multiple documents can exist in a single file/stream and are separated by `---`.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] An optional `...` can be used at the end of a file (useful for signaling an end in streamed communications without closing the pipe).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Because YAML primarily relies on outline indentation for structure, it is especially resistant to delimiter collision.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML may be placed in JSON by quoting and escaping all interior quotation marks.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML may be placed in XML by escaping reserved characters (`<`, `>`, `&`, `'`, `"`) and converting whitespace, or by placing it in a CDATA section.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Unlike JSON, which can only represent data in a hierarchical model with each child node having a single parent, YAML also offers a simple relational scheme that allows repeats of identical data to be referenced from two or more points in the tree rather than entered redundantly at those points.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] This is similar to the facility IDREF built into XML.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The YAML parser then expands these references into the fully populated data structures they imply when read in, so whatever program is using the parser does not have to be aware of a relational encoding model, unlike XML processors, which do not expand references.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] This expansion can enhance readability while reducing data entry errors in configuration files or processing protocols where many parameters remain the same in a sequential series of records while only a few vary.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] An example being that "ship-to" and "bill-to" records in an invoice are nearly always the same data.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML is purely a data-representation language and thus has no executable commands.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] While validation and safe parsing is inherently possible in any data language, implementation is such a notorious pitfall that YAML's lack of an associated command language may be a relative security benefit.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] However, YAML allows language-specific tags so that arbitrary local objects can be created by a parser that supports those tags.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Any YAML parser that allows sophisticated object instantiation to be executed opens the potential for an injection attack.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Perl parsers that allow loading of objects of arbitrary classes create so-called "blessed" values.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Using these values may trigger unexpected behavior, e.g. if the class uses overloaded operators.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] This may lead to execution of arbitrary Perl code.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The situation is similar for Python or Ruby parsers.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The YAML specification identifies an *instance document* as a "Presentation" or "character stream".
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The primary logical structures in a YAML instance document are scalars, sequences, and mappings.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The YAML specification also indicates some basic constraints that apply to these primary logical structures.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] For example, according to the specification, mapping keys do not have an order.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] In every case where node order is significant, a sequence must be used.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Moreover, in defining conformance for YAML processors, the YAML specification defines two primary operations: *dump* and *load*.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] All YAML-compliant processors must provide *at least* one of these operations, and may optionally provide both.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Finally, the YAML specification defines an *information model* or "representation graph", which must be created during processing for both *dump* and *load* operations, although this representation need not be made available to the user through an API.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] JSON syntax is a basis of YAML version 1.2, which was promulgated with the express purpose of bringing YAML "into compliance with JSON as an official subset".
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Though prior versions of YAML were not strictly compatible, the discrepancies were rarely noticeable, and most JSON documents can be parsed by some YAML parsers such as Syck.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] This is because JSON's semantic structure is equivalent to the optional "inline-style" of writing YAML.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] While extended hierarchies can be written in inline-style like JSON, this is not a recommended YAML style except when it aids clarity.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML has many additional features not present in JSON, including comments, extensible data types, relational anchors, strings without quotation marks, and mapping types preserving key order.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Due to the conciseness, JSON serialization and deserialization is much faster than YAML.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] TOML was designed to be an advancement of the .ini file format.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML makes minimal use of indicator characters compared to TOML's strict requirement of quotation marks and square brackets.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML's use of significant indentation has been contrasted with the dot notation of TOML's key and table names to convey the same semantic structure.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Opinions differ on which convention leads to more-readable configuration files.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML lacks the notion of tag attributes that are found in XML.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Instead YAML has extensible type declarations (including class types for objects).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML itself does not have XML's language-defined document schema descriptors that allow, for example, a document to self-validate.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] However, there are several externally defined schema descriptor languages for YAML (e.g.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Doctrine, Kwalify and Rx) that fulfill that role.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Moreover, the semantics provided by YAML's language-defined type declarations in the YAML document itself frequently relaxes the need for a validator in simple, common situations.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Additionally, YAXML, which represents YAML data structures in XML, allows XML schema importers and output mechanisms like XSLT to be applied to YAML.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Comparison of data-serialization formats provides a more comprehensive comparison of YAML with other serialization formats.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] For fixed data structures, YAML files can simply be generated using *print* commands that write both the data and the YAML specific decoration.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] To dump varying, or complex, hierarchical data, however, a dedicated YAML *emitter* is preferable.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Similarly, simple YAML files (e.g. key-value pairs) are readily parsed with regular expressions.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] For more complex, or varying, data structures, a formal YAML *parser* is recommended.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML emitters and parsers exist for many popular languages.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Most of them are written in the native language itself.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Some are language bindings of the C library *libyaml*; they may run faster.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] There used to be another C library, called *Syck*, written and orphaned by why the lucky stiff: it is unmaintained, there is no authoritative source bundle, and the web site has been hijacked.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Hence the only recommendable C library is *libyaml*.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] It was originally developed by Kirill Simonov.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] In 2018, development was resumed by the new maintainers Ian Cordasco and Ingy döt Net.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] C++ programmers have the choice between the C library *libyaml* and the C++ library *libyaml-cpp*.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Both have completely independent code bases and completely different APIs.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The library *libyaml-cpp* still has a major version number of 0, indicating that the API may change at any moment, as happened indeed after version 0.3.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] There is a grammar-focused implementation written in C#, with an aim on extensions for the nested elements.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Some implementations of YAML, such as Perl's YAML.pm, will load an entire file (stream) and parse it *en masse*.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Other implementations like PyYaml are lazy and iterate over the next document only upon request.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] For very large files in which one plans to handle the documents independently, instantiating the entire file before processing may be prohibitive.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] Thus in YAML.pm, occasionally one must chunk a file into documents and parse those individually.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] YAML makes this easy, since this simply requires splitting on the document end marker, which is defined as three periods at the start of a line followed by a whitespace (and possible a comment).
[src:hocon-config/yaml] In static, compiled languages, this instantiation is complex to achieve and is quite often not implemented.
[src:hocon-config/yaml] The perceived flaws and complexity of YAML has led to the emergence of stricter alternatives such as StrictYAML and NestedText.
